<script lang="ts">
	import MaterialsList from './components/MaterialsList.svelte';
	import DiscussionPrompts from './components/DiscussionPrompts.svelte';
	import ReflectionQuestions from './components/ReflectionQuestions.svelte';
	import AssessmentCriteria from './components/AssessmentCriteria.svelte';
	import CustomSection from './components/CustomSection.svelte';
	import { getSdgColor } from '$lib/utils/sdg-colors';

	interface Props {
		sdgColor?: string;
	}

	let { sdgColor = getSdgColor(9) }: Props = $props();
</script>

<div class="lesson-content">

	<MaterialsList materials={[{"name":"Spacious and safe dance studio or open classroom","isOptional":false},{"name":"A variety of instrumental music with different tempos and moods, suitable for improvisation and mirroring exercises","isOptional":false},{"name":"Whiteboard or large chart paper","isOptional":false},{"name":"Markers","isOptional":false},{"name":"Notebooks or paper","isOptional":false},{"name":"Pens/Pencils","isOptional":false}]} {sdgColor} />

	<CustomSection title={"Objectives"} content={"<strong>In this curriculum, students will:</strong><br><em>Knowledge</em><br><em> Develop a comprehensive understanding of Global Goal 9 (Industry, Innovation, and Infrastructure) and its critical importance for achieving sustainable development and improving human wellbeing globally. (NCCAS: Cr1.1.la, Cn10.1.la)<br></em> Gain awareness of the fundamental interconnectedness between robust and equitable infrastructure, inclusive and sustainable industrialization, and the fostering of innovation as drivers of progress. (NCCAS: Cn10.1.la, Cn11.1.la)<br><em> Explore the specific targets within Global Goal 9, including the development of quality,  resilient infrastructure, promoting sustainable and inclusive industrial practices, enhancing scientific research, and increasing access to technology and the internet. (NCCAS: Re7.1.la)<br></em> Learn about the diverse challenges and opportunities associated with achieving Global Goal 9 in different communities and countries, recognizing varying levels of development and capacity. (NCCAS: Cn10.1.la, Cn11.1.la)<br><em> Develop foundational knowledge of various creative disciplines, including drama, visual art, creative writing, dance, and music, and their potential as powerful tools for exploring and communicating complex themes related to development and progress. (NCCAS: Cr2.1.la)<br></em>Discourse<em><br></em> Analyze and interpret diverse forms of creative expression (drama, visual art, poetry, music, dance.) to identify and critically examine underlying themes, powerful messages, and varied perspectives related to infrastructure, industrialization, and innovation. (NCCAS: Re7.1.la, Re8.1.la)<br><em> Engage thoughtfully in nuanced discussions about complex issues related to infrastructure development, sustainable industrialization, technological innovation, and their societal and environmental impacts, demonstrating respect for diverse viewpoints.(NCCAS: Re9.1.la, Cn11.1.la)<br></em> Articulate their own devleoping ideas, insightful perspectives, and critical reflections on the challenges and opportunities within Global Goal 9 through both clear verbal and impactful nonverbal communication. (NCCAS: Pr5.1.la)<br><em> Collaborate effectively and creatively with peers to generate, develop, and share meaningful artistic projects that explore and respond to the multifaceted themes of Global Goal 9\\. (NCCAS: Cr3.1.la, Pr6.1.la)<br></em>Attitudes<em><br></em> Cultivate a strong sense of responsibility for promoting sustainable development and contributing to a more equitable, resilient, and prosperous future where infrastructure, industry, and innovation benefit all. (NCCAS: Cn11.1.la)<br><em> Develop a deepened appreciation for the transformative role of resilient infrastructure, sustainable industry, and continuous innovation in improving people's lives, fostering economic progress, and protecting the planet. (NCCAS: Cn10.1.la)<br></em> Foster a robust sense of global citizenship and a personal commitment to taking informed and creative action to achieve the Global Goals, recognizing the interconnectedness of global challenges and solutions. (NCCAS: Cn11.1.la)<br><em>Capacity</em><br><em> Enhance their creativity, critical thinking, problem-solving, and articulate communication skills through active and engaged participation in a variety of creative activities and collaborative projects focused on Global Goal 9 themes. (NCCAS: Cr2.1.la, Pr5.1.la)<br></em> Develop their analytical abilities to interpret information and diverse perspectives from various sources, including dramatic scenes, visual artwork, movement sequences, musical compositions, creative writing, and real-world examples related to infrastructure, industry, and innovation. (NCCAS: Re8.1.la)<br><em> Strengthen their capacity for meaningful self-expression and impactful creative communication through the thoughtful and purposeful use of various artistic mediums to explore and respond to the complexities of Global Goal 9\\. (NCCAS: Cr3.1.la)<br></em> Gain increased confidence in their ability to contribute to positive change and advocate for sustainable development and innovation within their communities and the wider world using artistic means. (NCCAS: Pr6.1.la)<br><em>Action</em><br><em> Identify age-appropriate and impactful actions they can take to promote the principles and targets of Global Goal 9 within their schools, communities, and beyond, considering both individual choices and collective advocacy. (NCCAS: Pr6.1.la, Cn11.1.la)<br></em> Explore and develop meaningful ways to use their creative skills and artistic voices to raise awareness, advocate for sustainable development, and inspire innovation that benefits all. (NCCAS: Cr3.1.la, Pr6.1.la)\n<ul>\n<li>Reflect thoughtfully on their individual and collective role in creating a more sustainable and innovative future for all, fostering a sense of sustained engagement and responsible global citizenship. (NCCAS: Re9.1.la, Cn11.1.la)</li>\n</ul><br><h2><strong>Mirroring Innovation: Exploring Sustainability Through Dance</strong></h2>"} {sdgColor} />

	<CustomSection title={"(30-60 MINUTES)"} content={"<strong>Introduction</strong><br>Begin with a dynamic warm-up to prepare student’ bodies for movement and get them energized. Include a variety of stretches, cardio exercises, and movement explorations.<br>Lead a movement-based icebreaker to foster a sense of connection and collaboration within the class.<br><em>Example:</em> Have students move around the room and greet each other with a unique movement or gesture.<br>Introduce the concept of mirroring in  movement and dance.<br>Key Points<br><em> Mirroring involves two or more people moving in sync with each other, reflecting each other’s movements like a mirror.<br></em> It requires focus, observation, and nonverbal communication.<br><em> It can be used to build trust, empathy, and connection.<br></em> It can be applied creatively to express ideas and emotions.<br>Guiding Questions<br><em> What are some examples of mirroring in everyday life? (e.g., conversations, social interactions)<br></em> How can mirroring be used to communicate without words?<br><em> What are some of the benefits of mirroring in dance and movement?<br>Introduce/re-introduce Global Goal 9: Industry, Innovation, and Infrastructure. Explain the core idea of building resilient infrastructure, promoting inclusive and sustainable industrialization, and fostering innovation.<br>Briefly introduce the different targets within Global Goal 9, highlighting their interconnectedness and importance.<br>Guiding Questions<br></em> What are some of the challenges in achieving these targets?\n<ul>\n<li>How might these targets affect different people and communities around the world?</li>\n</ul>"} {sdgColor} />

	<CustomSection title={"Exploring Mirroring Techniques"} content={"<em>Basic Mirroring</em><br><em> Pair students up and have them practice basic mirroring exercises.<br></em> One student is the leader, and the other is the follower.<br><em> The leader initiates movements, and the follower mirrors them as closely as possible.<br>Encourage students to focus on clarity, precision, and nonverbal communication.<br></em> Ensure both students have a chance to play both roles.<br>Guiding Questions<br><em> What are some of the challenges of mirroring?<br></em> How can you improve your mirroring skills?<br><em> How does it feel to be the leader versus the follower?<br></em>Mirroring with Variations<em><br>Introduce variations to the mirroring exercises, such as:<br></em> Changing roles mid-mirror (without stopping the movement) (leder and follower switch).<br><em> Adding levels (high, medium, low).<br></em> Incorporating different qualities of movement (smooth, sharp, fluid, bound).<br><em> Adding emotional expression to the movement.<br>Guiding Questions<br></em> How do these variations affect the mirroring experience?<br><em> How can you use mirroring to express different ideas or emotions?<br>Discuss how mirroring can be used to create a sense of connection and empathy between partners.<br>Encourage students to pay attention to their partner’s movements and energy, and to respond in a way that shows understanding and support.<br>Guiding Questions<br></em> How does mirroring help you understand your partner better?\n<ul>\n<li>How can you use mirroring to build trust and support?</li>\n</ul>"} {sdgColor} />

	<CustomSection title={"Mirroring and Global Goal 9"} content={"<p>Facilitate a brainstorming session where students generate ideas for how mirroring can be used to represent the different targets within Global Goal 9\\.<br>Guiding Questions<br><em> What are some movements qualities or dynamics that could represent each target?<br></em> How can we use mirroring to convey the challenges and opportunities associated with each target?<br><em> How can we use mirroring to express the interconnectedness of the different targets within Global Goal 9?<br></em>Examples<em><br></em> <strong>Target 9.1</strong> <em>(Resilient Infrastructure):</em> Create a mirroring sequence where partners support and balance each other, representing the strength and stability of resilient infrastructure.<br><em> <strong>Target 9.2</strong> </em>(Access to Financial Services):<em> Develop a mirroring exercise where partners take turns leading and following, representing the collaborative nature of inclusive industrialization.<br></em> <strong>Target 9.3</strong> <em>(Access to Financial Services):</em> Create a mirroring sequence where one partner supports the other to reach higher, symbolizing access to resources and opportunities.<br><em> <strong>Target 9.4</strong> </em>(Sustainable Infrastructure):<em> Develop a mirroring exercise where partners move in a fluid and interconnected way, representing the flow of resources and energy in a sustainable system.<br></em> <strong>Target 9.5</strong> <em>(Innovation):</em> Create a mirroring sequence with unexpected changes and variations, representing the dynamic and evolving nature of innovation.<br><em> <strong>Target 9.a</strong> </em>(Infrastructure Development in Developing Countries):<em> Develop a mirroring exercise where partners help each other overcome obstacles, representing the support and collaboration needed for infrastructure development.<br></em> <strong>Target 9.b</strong> <em>(Domestic Technology Development):</em> Create a mirroring sequence where partners build on each other’s movements, representing the growth and advancement of technology.<br><em> <strong>Target 9.c</strong> </em>(Access to Information and Communications Technology):* Develop a mirroring exercise where partners communicate through movement, representing the flow of information and ideas.<br>Divide students into pairs or small groups. Each pair/group selects or is assigned one target from Global Goal 9 (or can focus on the Goal holistically) and creates a movement piece using mirroring techniques to represent a specific aspect of that target/goal.<br>Encourage students to be creative and expressive in their movement choices, using mirroring to convey the essence of their chosen target.<br>Provide time for students to rehearse and refine their movement pieces.</p>"} {sdgColor} />

	<DiscussionPrompts prompts={["What were some of the most powerful or memorable movement pieces you saw?","How did these pieces make you think differently about Global Goal 9?","What were some of the common themes or messages you noticed in the movement?","How did the use of mirroring enhance the expression of ideas and emotions?"]} {sdgColor} />

	<ReflectionQuestions questions={["How did the practice of mirroring \\- reflecting another person’s movements \\- help you understand the concept of collaboration and interconnectedness that is central to Global Goal 9?","What did you learn about non-verbal communication and empathy through mirroring? How might these skills be important in building global partnerships for innovation and infrastructure?","How did physically embodying different aspects of Global Goal 9 (e.g., resilient infrastructure, innovation, technology transfer) change your understanding of those concepts?","Did the act of moving in sync with a partner create a sense of unity or shared purpose? How does this relate to the idea of countries or organizations working together?","What did you discover about the challenges and rewards of adapting to another person’s movements in the mirroring exercises?","What new insights did you gain about Global Goal 9 and the importance of industry, innovation, and infrastructure through the movement exploration?","How did the different mirroring sequences created by your group or others vividly represent the challenges or opportunities within Global Goal 9 and its targets?","Can you identify how mirroring, as a metaphor, illustrates the transfer of technology, the building of capacity, or the integration of different ideas in a partnership?","What role do you think shared understanding and aligned actions (like in mirroring) play in achieving sustainable industrialization or resilient infrastructure?","How did connecting to abstract concepts help you to see the human element within the goals of industry, innovation, and infrastructure?","Did any specific mirroring experience or movement sequence resonate with you on a personal level, perhaps connecting to teamwork or problem-solving in your own life?","What did you learn about your own capacity for adaptability and creative problem-solving through this movement activity?","What are some ways that you can continue to use movement, dance, or collaborative thinking to raise awareness or advocate for Global Goal 9 in your daily life?"]} {sdgColor} />

	<AssessmentCriteria criteria={["Consistent and enthusiastic involvement in all phases of the lesson, including the warm-up, mirroring exercises, creative movement, and class discussions.","Comprehension of Global Goal 9 and its targets and core concepts. This can be evidenced by the symbolism and intention within the movement pieces and the verbal explanations during sharing and discussion.","Originality and effectiveness in using mirroring techniques (e.g., precise reflection, leading/following variations, incorporating levels/qualities) to convey their chosen message about industry, innovation, and/or infrastructure.","How clearly and powerfully the finished movement pieces communicate the intended message. Look for the ability of the movement to evoke thought or emotion related to Global Goal 9\\.","Ability to work effectively with others, demonstrating active listening, responsiveness, and mutual support during the mirroring and creative movement phases.","Nuance and insight demonstrated in their reflections, particularly concerning the role of embodied learning in understanding global challenges and the importance of collaboration in achieving sustainable development."]} {sdgColor} />

	<CustomSection title={"Mirroring Innovation: Exploring Sustainability Through Dance"} content={"<strong>(30-60 MINUTES)</strong><br><strong>Introduction</strong><br>Begin with a dynamic warm-up to prepare student’ bodies for movement and get them energized. Include a variety of stretches, cardio exercises, and movement explorations.<br>Lead a movement-based icebreaker to foster a sense of connection and collaboration within the class.<br><em>Example:</em> Have students move around the room and greet each other with a unique movement or gesture.<br>Introduce the concept of mirroring in  movement and dance.<br>Key Points<br><em> Mirroring involves two or more people moving in sync with each other, reflecting each other’s movements like a mirror.<br></em> It requires focus, observation, and nonverbal communication.<br><em> It can be used to build trust, empathy, and connection.<br></em> It can be applied creatively to express ideas and emotions.<br>Guiding Questions<br><em> What are some examples of mirroring in everyday life? (e.g., conversations, social interactions)<br></em> How can mirroring be used to communicate without words?<br><em> What are some of the benefits of mirroring in dance and movement?<br>Introduce/re-introduce Global Goal 9: Industry, Innovation, and Infrastructure. Explain the core idea of building resilient infrastructure, promoting inclusive and sustainable industrialization, and fostering innovation.<br>Briefly introduce the different targets within Global Goal 9, highlighting their interconnectedness and importance.<br>Guiding Questions<br></em> What are some of the challenges in achieving these targets?<br><em> How might these targets affect different people and communities around the world?<br><strong>Exploring Mirroring Techniques</strong><br></em>Basic Mirroring<em><br></em> Pair students up and have them practice basic mirroring exercises.<br><em> One student is the leader, and the other is the follower.<br></em> The leader initiates movements, and the follower mirrors them as closely as possible.<br>Encourage students to focus on clarity, precision, and nonverbal communication.<br><em> Ensure both students have a chance to play both roles.<br>Guiding Questions<br></em> What are some of the challenges of mirroring?<br><em> How can you improve your mirroring skills?<br></em> How does it feel to be the leader versus the follower?<br><em>Mirroring with Variations</em><br>Introduce variations to the mirroring exercises, such as:<br><em> Changing roles mid-mirror (without stopping the movement) (leder and follower switch).<br></em> Adding levels (high, medium, low).<br><em> Incorporating different qualities of movement (smooth, sharp, fluid, bound).<br></em> Adding emotional expression to the movement.<br>Guiding Questions<br><em> How do these variations affect the mirroring experience?<br></em> How can you use mirroring to express different ideas or emotions?<br>Discuss how mirroring can be used to create a sense of connection and empathy between partners.<br>Encourage students to pay attention to their partner’s movements and energy, and to respond in a way that shows understanding and support.<br>Guiding Questions<br><em> How does mirroring help you understand your partner better?<br></em> How can you use mirroring to build trust and support?<br><strong>Mirroring and Global Goal 9</strong><br>Facilitate a brainstorming session where students generate ideas for how mirroring can be used to represent the different targets within Global Goal 9\\.<br>Guiding Questions<br><em> What are some movements qualities or dynamics that could represent each target?<br></em> How can we use mirroring to convey the challenges and opportunities associated with each target?<br><em> How can we use mirroring to express the interconnectedness of the different targets within Global Goal 9?<br></em>Examples<em><br></em> <strong>Target 9.1</strong> <em>(Resilient Infrastructure):</em> Create a mirroring sequence where partners support and balance each other, representing the strength and stability of resilient infrastructure.<br><em> <strong>Target 9.2</strong> </em>(Access to Financial Services):<em> Develop a mirroring exercise where partners take turns leading and following, representing the collaborative nature of inclusive industrialization.<br></em> <strong>Target 9.3</strong> <em>(Access to Financial Services):</em> Create a mirroring sequence where one partner supports the other to reach higher, symbolizing access to resources and opportunities.<br><em> <strong>Target 9.4</strong> </em>(Sustainable Infrastructure):<em> Develop a mirroring exercise where partners move in a fluid and interconnected way, representing the flow of resources and energy in a sustainable system.<br></em> <strong>Target 9.5</strong> <em>(Innovation):</em> Create a mirroring sequence with unexpected changes and variations, representing the dynamic and evolving nature of innovation.<br><em> <strong>Target 9.a</strong> </em>(Infrastructure Development in Developing Countries):<em> Develop a mirroring exercise where partners help each other overcome obstacles, representing the support and collaboration needed for infrastructure development.<br></em> <strong>Target 9.b</strong> <em>(Domestic Technology Development):</em> Create a mirroring sequence where partners build on each other’s movements, representing the growth and advancement of technology.<br><em> <strong>Target 9.c</strong> </em>(Access to Information and Communications Technology):<em> Develop a mirroring exercise where partners communicate through movement, representing the flow of information and ideas.<br>Divide students into pairs or small groups. Each pair/group selects or is assigned one target from Global Goal 9 (or can focus on the Goal holistically) and creates a movement piece using mirroring techniques to represent a specific aspect of that target/goal.<br>Encourage students to be creative and expressive in their movement choices, using mirroring to convey the essence of their chosen target.<br>Provide time for students to rehearse and refine their movement pieces.<br><strong>Sharing and Discussion</strong><br>Have each pair/group share their movement piece with the class. Encourage the audience to observe carefully and reflect on the messages and emotions conveyed through the movement.<br>Facilitate a class discussion about the movement pieces, focusing on the connection to Global Goal 9, the effectiveness of mirroring techniques, and the overall impact of the performances.<br>Guiding Questions<br></em> What were some of the most powerful or memorable movement pieces you saw?<br><em> How did these pieces make you think differently about Global Goal 9?<br></em> What were some of the common themes or messages you noticed in the movement?<br><em> How did the use of mirroring enhance the expression of ideas and emotions?<br><strong>Reflection and Summary</strong><br>Have students reflect on their learning experience through discussion or writing.<br>Ask guiding questions like:<br></em> How did the practice of mirroring \\- reflecting another person’s movements \\- help you understand the concept of collaboration and interconnectedness that is central to Global Goal 9?<br><em> What did you learn about non-verbal communication and empathy through mirroring? How might these skills be important in building global partnerships for innovation and infrastructure?<br></em> How did physically embodying different aspects of Global Goal 9 (e.g., resilient infrastructure, innovation, technology transfer) change your understanding of those concepts?<br><em> Did the act of moving in sync with a partner create a sense of unity or shared purpose? How does this relate to the idea of countries or organizations working together?<br></em> What did you discover about the challenges and rewards of adapting to another person’s movements in the mirroring exercises?<br><em> What new insights did you gain about Global Goal 9 and the importance of industry, innovation, and infrastructure through the movement exploration?<br></em> How did the different mirroring sequences created by your group or others vividly represent the challenges or opportunities within Global Goal 9 and its targets?<br><em> Can you identify how mirroring, as a metaphor, illustrates the transfer of technology, the building of capacity, or the integration of different ideas in a partnership?<br></em> What role do you think shared understanding and aligned actions (like in mirroring) play in achieving sustainable industrialization or resilient infrastructure?<br><em> How did connecting to abstract concepts help you to see the human element within the goals of industry, innovation, and infrastructure?<br></em> Did any specific mirroring experience or movement sequence resonate with you on a personal level, perhaps connecting to teamwork or problem-solving in your own life?<br><em> What did you learn about your own capacity for adaptability and creative problem-solving through this movement activity?<br></em> What are some ways that you can continue to use movement, dance, or collaborative thinking to raise awareness or advocate for Global Goal 9 in your daily life?<br><strong>Assessment</strong><br><em> Consistent and enthusiastic involvement in all phases of the lesson, including the warm-up, mirroring exercises, creative movement, and class discussions.<br></em> Comprehension of Global Goal 9 and its targets and core concepts. This can be evidenced by the symbolism and intention within the movement pieces and the verbal explanations during sharing and discussion.<br><em> Originality and effectiveness in using mirroring techniques (e.g., precise reflection, leading/following variations, incorporating levels/qualities) to convey their chosen message about industry, innovation, and/or infrastructure.<br></em> How clearly and powerfully the finished movement pieces communicate the intended message. Look for the ability of the movement to evoke thought or emotion related to Global Goal 9\\.<br><em> Ability to work effectively with others, demonstrating active listening, responsiveness, and mutual support during the mirroring and creative movement phases.<br></em> Nuance and insight demonstrated in their reflections, particularly concerning the role of embodied learning in understanding global challenges and the importance of collaboration in achieving sustainable development."} {sdgColor} />

</div>
